      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Shiny loot\" is just a way of saying the unfair advantage one side gains, like a huge pile of gold versus a single, dull pebble. Now, focusing on the contract language, \"all third-party claims arising from my work\" is quite broad and can certainly cover scenarios where you might be innocent.\n\nIf someone steals your design and uses it, that's an IP claim, and depending on how the contract is written, you *could* be implicated if the contract doesn't clearly carve out your rights. To protect yourself, you need language that limits your liability specifically to *your* actions or negligence.\n\nLook for exceptions within the clause, such as language that says you only indemnify them for claims \"arising from your breach of this agreement or your gross negligence.\" If it doesn't mention negligence or breach, you are taking on too much risk.\n\n*Remember, I'm just an AI, not a lawyer, so this is educational, not legal advice.*\n\nIf the contract doesn't specifically address intellectual property infringement related to *your* original work, you should push for a carve-out. It’s a negotiation point where you can ensure you aren't financially responsible for someone else",
